<Author>Swamprats
<Content>Two Flew Into the Cuckoo's Nest Bahia Salinas is rather unique by virtue of the scenery and location, but we knew we were in trouble when we spotted employees dressed like orderlies, ostensibly to tend to those of us that were bonkers enough to pay the grotesquely high rates. Our room was well-appointed but only a munchkin with a two-by-four for back support would appreciate the saggy bed and miniscule dimensions. Our poolside waiter was a trainee and took the better part of an hour to produce a Coke minus the rum. The desk clerk promised a kayak but the the kayak person didn't show up. I have my own kayak but to use it is strictly verboten. The pool cleaner started cleaning at 7 a.m. on our last day and was still cleaning when we finally abandoned all hope of a cool dip by 11 a.m. and checked out. (photo attached). Bring along some nuclear mosquito repellent or you will be devoured before you finish the appetizer of your sunset dinner. $9 will get you a bottle from the gift shop. Our waiter mercifully let us borrow the house DDT, otherwise we would have succumbed to malaria before counting out the tip. In spite of it all, the charm and beauty of the place manages to transcend it's idiosychrasies, that is as long as you enjoy the smell of sulphur in the morning as you gaze down from the balcony upon a decrepit outdoor collection of tanks and machinery. It also helps if you are up to a long hike to the Cabo Rojo lighthouse in the blazing sun. I have to admit that the food was great and we drank enough wine (that my son ordered by phone from Miami) to forget the aggravation and enjoy our 31st anniversary. As you can tell we loved and hated it all at once. That is the Puerto Rico experience. 
