<Author>tropicalgardener
<Content>The office staff 'misplaced' [stole] my daughter's phone! DO NOT STAY HERE FRIEND...READ ON,Where do I start with this overpriced dump?First, my daughter left her bookbag in the office upon checkout. When we called, nobody knew about the bag. We called again. Oh, the bag was found. Was the cell phone with the bag? Yes. Could you please mail it to us and bill our room? Certainly. Waited a week, called. Woman said she could not mail without charge card number. I politely told her to use the one her business used to charge our room. Waited a week more, nothing. Called, she claimed Federal Express had not come by. Frustrated, I drove for two hours across the island to pick up the bag myself. When I got there, the phone was missing, though two of the female employees had seen the phone, safe behind the office desk. Nobody could say where the phone was since anything was possible! The manager/owner was, naturally, on a trip to San Juan. We left. I have been calling for over two weeks now. In the U.S. I would have called the police. What a nasty experience. This hotel owner has no moral, no standards, no class. I wish I could report him to...someone. Truth is: In Puerto Rico, Americans get ripped off on the regular-even by so-called nice places like this moth-bug infested hellhole.Second, you can't go in the water because it is...toxic. Really, you cannot go in the bug-infested water in front the the spa because it contains dangerous microbes, too near the mangrove and salt flats. The water stinks and is murky.We paid way too much for our nasty room. I woke up with hotel throat, though the place is supposed to be some sort of spa. For the same price, in Mexico, you can stay in a truly wonderful hotel. Not this dump.Guess what: we should have known better. We checked in on a weekday, thought at the height of the tourist season-not another guest the whole time. The manager glared at my well-behaved children splashing in the deserted pool. It was clear the place was structured for the singles set, or honeymooners. I cannot imagine spending a honeymoon in this dump.The truth is this: If you took this place and set it down in an area not infested with bugs and crawling, slimy things, it might be kind of nice. But then you would still have the surly workers, and dishonest management/owner.When we checked in, the woman acted as if we were disturbing some great moment. But this is typical of the Puerto Rican hotel workers; they obviously hate their jobs and could give a rat's butt about customers.The salt flats are very interesting, if a bit deserted and not safe for families. The local beaches are really quite wonderful, but I would perhaps stay in Rincon next time-which I usually do.This place has bad vibes, and I am guessing it starts with the owner. By the way, for the prices you pay, the restaurant kind of sucks, too, and the service is lame.Again, you would be better off heading to Rincon.I call every day, but the manager/owner refuses to return my calls. Maybe the workers are not giving him the message?Welcome to Puerto Rico! 
