<Author>freckledtrekker
<Content>Guests' comfort is a very low priority, much better deals elsewhere in area My wife and I are not nit-picky travelers incapable of rolling with the punches; we are used to adapting to things being different than anticipated when we travel. However, our recent experience at the Bahia Salinas Beach Resort and Spa (BSBRS) in December 2007 tested our endurance dearly, and since we paid $174 for the pleasure (the cost of one night鈥檚 stay, though we checked out three hours after check-in without even spending the night), we feel entitled, and dare I say it -- obligated -- to share with you why you must avoid this place at all costs.Unlike what its website suggests, BSBRS, an apparent one-time motor motel converted unconvincingly into a purportedly upscale retreat on a very narrow and skanky spit of land, is far from an oasis of peace and relaxation. Here is what we encountered upon check-in at 4 pm on a Saturday in December 2007:1) an outdoor wedding reception, replete with track after track of heavy-bass dance music, in the hotel鈥檚 very narrow courtyard, on which virtually all rooms and the 鈥渞elaxation鈥?spa at the hotel face directly and in very close proximity. Having nothing else to bounce off of other than the very thin walls and windows of the guests鈥?rooms, the soundwaves easily penetrated into our second-floor hotel room, causing us deafening reverberations while we entertained our very first thoughts of checking out and fleeing. When we complained about this politely and immediately at the front desk, we were told a) just to endure it, it would be over by 11 pm at the latest, or b) to come see the only other room available (which we did, and it was closer to the loud music, without a single window, and dark and depressing). When I then asked about reducing our stay from the scheduled three nights to just one or possibly even zero nights, they said they could not refund our money, even though nights #2 and #3 had been paid for only 10 minutes prior, at check-in. I am sure they could have refunded it to us had they wanted to, both because the credit card authorizations for the day could not have yet been finalized, and because you would think they would feel ashamed of the loud noise to which guests were being going to be subjected for some 7 hours straight. Furthermore, when I raised the matter of how unconscionable it was for them to book a wedding right in the courtyard, the front desk staff person was totally unapologetic about it. As someone who himself runs a public facility back in Texas, I can tell you that this hotel should not even be in the business of hosting wedding receptions, because there is nowhere to hold them on this hotel鈥檚 property (other than the restaurant across the parking lot) that will not interfere with the quiet and relaxation of the hotel鈥檚 other guests. The hotel management is being financially greedy and self-centered to book weddings here, in blatant disregard of the other guests鈥?comfort.2) our hotel room had a piercingly toxic, plasticky smell that would not go away no matter how much we aired it out3) due to technical problems, the hotel could not process American Express cards at time of check-in, and though the staff had known of this issue for days and I had used an AmEx card for my hotel deposit several weeks earlier, no one thought to call us and tell us ahead of time to forewarn that we must bring another form of payment. On top of that financial inconvenience, I was also out a 3% rebate that my AmEx card provides me when I use it to pay for hotel stays, and the hotel staff didn鈥檛 care about that point either.4) the hotel has a plethora of rules and policies designed for the convenience of hotel staff over that of its guests: all swim towels must be returned to the front desk by 9:00 pm every day (rather than at end of stay, as is normal at other hotels), the pool closes at an ungodly early 7:00 pm, etc.So, having checked in at 4:00 pm, by about 7:00 pm we had verified with Visa that they would reverse the charge for nights #2 and #3, had loaded all our luggage back into our car, and had turned in our room key to the new front desk person, telling them 鈥渢his is what your hotel gets for booking an obnoxiously loud wedding in the courtyard 鈥?now you鈥檙e out our two nights鈥?room charges plus whatever else we would have spent here on drinks and meals鈥? Already nighttime, we drove eastward toward Guanica, where we had a delightful three-day stay (at a lower rack rate than BSBRS!) at the Copamarina Beach Resort, where guests鈥?comfort and convenience are paramount, the rooms are large, peaceful, and delightful, and nothing obnoxiously loud is tolerated. 
