<Content>Fantastic if you know what to expect I spent 4 nights mid-week in June with my family in two rooms (next to each other in front of the kids' pool). I say mid-week and it is important because (this was my first stay in PR) I now understand that resorts and resort towns are completely dead during the week and get busy at the week end. So we had the resort for ourselves and it was great. The resort is between the salt flats (in exploitation) and the sea. The beach is swampy but the view is to die for. There are nice beaches on both sides (accessible by car or walking), bring your bug spray. The view from the cliffs and the lighthouse are great. There is not much to do in the hotel (this is not really a resort, kayaks and ping pong tables would not hurt), it is remote and relaxing. Service is friendly. Staff finds it difficult to get out of the routine, but the routine is good enough. Food in the evening is good if the chef is in good mood and does not want to close the kitchen too early (again, mid-week). Go to Joyuda Beach or La Parguera for more choice. The peninsula on which the hotel sits is just incredible for jogging, cycling or walking in a nature preserve. The rooms are big (ours had no phone). Next year they plan to add 38 villas, it could get more crowded. All in all, this is a Parador, inexpensive for what you get, in the middle of the most incredible nature settings in PR. 
