<Author>commodora
<Content>Special place! Bahia Salinas Resort and Spa is gorgeous and perfectly maintained. It is built facing a calm mangrove bay with swimming in a limited section.. Constructed only in 1998 with 27 rooms, two pools, one an infinity pool, a bar, contintental restaurant, (an Italian restaurant is due to open shortly we were told) and spa, it is romantic, , with lush gardens and an attentive staff. They are constantly cleaning and tending to the gardens, cleaning the pools, etc.The hotel is a three hour car ride from San Juan airport. Located in the southwest tip of P.R., it is a perfect get a way for a few days.After sailing a charter boat in the B. V. I's for 10 days, we arrived for R and R at the resort on Jan 16, Tuesday to Saturday a.m., which turned out to be low season. They said they had five rooms rented. We saw a few Norte Americans over the next 4 days, but had the pool to ourselves for the most part for the few hours we spent there.Breakfast is buffet style. Made to order eggs. Bacon, ham, home fries. Fruit, cereal, pastry, etc.Check to make sure they are serving lunch the days you are there. We slept through breakfast the first day, arrived for lunch at 12 and discovered no lunch service, but the chef or cook who was there made us good sliced chicken sandwiches and fries. If lunch is not on the off season schedule, stop in a local mercado (supermarket) and pick up cheese, vacuum packed salami, etc and crackers or whatever works for you. We used ice buckets to keep the perishables cool. Soda/drinks help too. The local nectars are delicious and cheap.What we ended up paying for the four nights turned out to be less than what was quoted on the web site, about $30 less per dayI Best to call the resort for a quote first. It's a US call on the cell phone, no extra charge. 878 254 1212. They speak English.See the photos on the forum page.If you want to pull yourself away from the pool, walk down the beach to a white sand beach which has snorkeling (bring your gear). Or drive a mile further south to the restored Cabo Rojo Lighthouse. It is not open for admission yet and the road is a challenge to get there, but doable if you drive slowly. Park below the lighthouse, walk up the stone path and walk around the lighthouse for spectacular views. Then see the perfect beach cove near where you parked. If you have brought towels or a fishing rod, enjoy the serenity. Unless it is a weekend--I understand the Puerto Rican people pull up in their boats and unload their jet skis to spoil the ambiance.La Parguera is a 40 minute car ride. That is where you go for the ride to the Bioluminescent Bay. To get there, use the map the hotel has. The boats go out an hour or so after sunset. Wear a bathing suit and go out on the smaller boat (22 passengers)that goes into the mangroves. You will be closer to the water even if you choose to not swim. Get a bite or drink before at Yolanda's, up the street from the boat marina. Yolanda's is owned and managed by Antonia DiLillo from Toms River NJ area. Great burgers and fries, nice guy.Boqeron is a beautiful beach about 20 minutes north (admission with car $3, nothing to walk in) bordered by a ramshackle looking town. Some restaurants overlooking the waterlooked decent though.Joyuda Beach was 40 minutes north of the resort. We went there to watch the sunset and get dinner at Bahia Vista Restaurant. It's claim to fame, besides the sunsets, is the 50 or so tarpon that swim around the deck pounching on pitched over the railing tidbits from the diners above. Oh for a fishing rod!Do not even think of stopping in Mayaguez, one hour north of the resort . What a disappointment. The old town and port is worse than a slum and the two hotel casinos a bit north of the city are a disappointment. They do have pools on the grounds and the Mayaguez Resort is building a water slide and assorted other water goodies to attract families with kids. Could not find a town center with any decent shopping or anything that would make me want to get out of the car. Shopping is wonderful in old town San Juan and San Juan is worth repeated stays for a few days of R and R and an easy escape from the northern winters.Getting to the resort: Use the directions they will send you and get a map from the car rental place. We drove south from the airport, through Ponce in the south, then west. We returned to San Juan using Route 2 going north, then connected with 22, the super highway, which has no lights, and allowed us to make it to the car rental place 2 1/2 hours before our flight. We allowed 5 hours for the ride back because we meandered off the road to explore sites of future stays. Nothing appealed. We would go back to Bahia Salinas Resort and Spa, maybe in February and over a weekend, when things are busier. 
