<Author>Matador
<Content>Bahia Salinas Resort: great place, great location, but lacking in service Since I find these reviews to be rather useful, particularly the detailed ones, below is a rather wordy summary of my recent stay at the Bahia Salinas. The first paragraph is the 鈥渃ut to the chase鈥?version鈥?br/>I would recommend this Resort, with several caveats. Pros: Hotel grounds are well maintained and aesthetically pleasing; infinity pool was very nice; staff is friendly; I would rate the restaurant very good to excellent in terns of the dinner food. Cons: Can鈥檛 swim in the beach in front of the hotel; service was slow, and on a few occasions terrible; after 6pm have your Deep Woods Off handy to repel the mosquitoes. I鈥檒l leave the evaluation of the rooms in the details below, as that is subject to personal taste. Now for the 鈥渨ordy鈥?version鈥?br/>First Impression:We were 2 families. The adults are in their [early] forties, and the children (all boys), are 13, 13, and 17. Our stay was for a Sat-Sat. Both opted for the meal plan. As soon as we checked in, we were impressed with the grounds. As we walked to our rooms, we passed the infinity pool and couldn鈥檛 wait to jump in. Rooms:The rooms were clean, and IMO simply, but tastefully furnished. There are no phones or clock radios in the rooms. And the TV has limited cable (ie. no ESPN). Some might find that a con, and some might like it. Since there is nothing to do in the evening, a little Sportscenter before bed would have been nice. You could hang meat in the rooms with the air conditioning, but you can adjust it (from cold to not as cold鈥鈥檇 rather have that extreme than an inadequate system). Both families initially opted for the divided queen rooms. There is one bedroom when you enter, and the bathroom is between that and the 2nd bedroom for privacy. The trade off is space. Both BRs are small, and there is little closet space. My friends had the same layout, but since their room was in between other rooms, the back bedroom had no windows, making it very claustrophobic (ours was at then end, so both BRs had windows). They changed to a 鈥榮uite鈥?which was basically a single room, with 2 queen beds (no divider), and room for a desk and chair. Hammocks and rocking chairs in front of the rooms was a nice touch. The bathroom toiletries were a pleasant surprise.Amenities:As I mentioned, the infinity pool is very nice, and was never crowded during our stay. I suspect that with only 22 rooms, if you factor in guests coming in and out, and some hanging out by the kiddie pool, or at the bar, the pool can never get crowded. The spa and beauty salon were open during our stay, but we did not get a chance to take advantage of them. Poolside towels were easily available at the front desk (must be returned before the end of the day). The public poolside bathrooms were immaculate. And although there is no swimmable beach in front of the hotel, you will find one of the most picturesque beaches in all of PR a short (and bumpy) drive from the hotel. It is nestled between 2 cliffs, one of which has the famous lighthouse. You can walk it from the hotel (its about 1 mile), just take enough liquids for the walk to and fro.Food Service:Here is where it goes downhill. Breakfast was fine: simple buffet, though I would prefer some other options for drinks other than water, orange juice or coffee. Service varied, but not enough to give breakfast a negative review. Lunch, on the other hand, was not worth it. The service was horrendous. We waited at least 90 minutes for things as simple as hot dogs and grilled chicken sandwiches. One person ordered the grilled chicken over greens (in lieu of sandwich), and had to wait extra, only to be served sliced chicken breast cold cuts over lettuce. Upon complaining, it took 10 minutes to get what she initially ordered. Might have been OK had we gotten some drink service, but upon serving half the table with Pina Coladas, the other half was left drinkless. And all they ordered were cokes! In all fairness, they only have one person who serves as the waiter, bartender and busboy. But there is no excuse for the delay in the food鈥houldn鈥檛 take 90 minutes to cook a hotdog. And it wasn鈥檛 like there was a large crowd either. Dinner was very good, but again the service was a bit slow. There is a difference between 鈥渟low鈥?service and bad service, and they were walking that fine line during dinner. The food, however, was very good and offset the 鈥渓eisurely鈥?pace.Last word:If you want something quiet, comfortable, relaxing, and off the beaten path, Bahia Salinas is for you. If you stay here, you are probably the adventurous type and/or are quite familiar with the area. As such, I would not recommend the meal plan. Have breakfast at the hotel, but for lunch venture out and try some of the local fare (we discovered 鈥淎ntojitos Evel鈥?in El Combate to be a favorite amongst the locals, and rightfully so). Certainly have at least one dinner at the restaurant, but there are other options in the general surroundings. The service notwithstanding, I personally would not opt for the meal plan since I hate being on a schedule. I prefer the flexibility of eating when and where the mood strikes. The place has a 3-star rating, which I think is fair since in some areas it exceeded the rating, and in some it did not meet it. If they would improve their food/bar service, this would be a great place to stay (rather than just 鈥渞ecommended鈥?. That, and ESPN ;-) 
